{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d0fe2ba4-c5e6-49c1-abee-4cd076be52e8","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed:\n\n1. **Crash reports (`.ips` files)** are saved by `ReportCrash` to:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user apps)\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system/root apps)\n\n2. **Find the latest one:**\n   ```bash\n   ls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n   ```\n\n3. **Core dumps** can also be enabled, but are off by default on macOS:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Cores go to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\nThe `.ips` crash log includes the exception type, faulting thread, and full native backtrace. If you need to symbolicate the .NET runtime frames in that `.ips` file, I can help with that too — just share the file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"10708dc4-a069-4e2f-bdf6-6ffa3a3ccfb2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to search the codebase for this.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":329,"requestId":"1B80:75BF8:E421C6:103A548:6A0286DF"},"id":"865150cf-0538-40cd-8a9f-cd195173acaf","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:48:24.913Z","parentId":"968519ba-98db-455b-93bc-b0386fb1d28a"}
